## Category 9: Agent Workflow Anti-Patterns

### 9.1 UI-First Development Anti-Pattern (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Start with core logic/domain layer implementation before building UI layers.

❌ Bad: Building UI/extension first, starting with complex frontend before core logic works, UI tightly coupled to business logic, SwiftUI views before domain layer exists
✅ Good: Core logic first (CLI, domain layer, or testable interfaces), verify logic works, then build UI/extensions, keep UI as thin layer; for iOS/Swift: Domain layer (Pure Swift) first, then Presentation layer (SwiftUI)
⚠️ Why: Core logic layer allows agents to test and verify directly; UI-first delays verification and adds complexity; agents work faster with testable interfaces; domain layer enables proper separation of concerns
🔧 Fix: Always start with core logic/domain layer for core functionality; build UI after logic is proven and working; for iOS/Swift: build Pure Swift domain layer before SwiftUI presentation layer

**Exception:** Pure UI apps with minimal business logic may iterate rapidly between UI and logic.

📍 See: `engineering-philosophy.mdc` section 1.5, `swift-5-9-development-standards.mdc` section "Architectural Layers"

**Detect:** Starting with UI/extension code, building frontend before core logic works, no way to test logic directly, business logic in UI layer, SwiftUI views importing SwiftData/MusicKit directly, domain layer importing SwiftUI

---

### 9.2 Verbose Text-Only Prompts (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Use visual aids (screenshots, images) for UI/design work instead of lengthy text descriptions.

❌ Bad: Long text descriptions of UI issues, 500-word prompt explaining visual problems, trying to describe visual problems in words, verbose explanations when image would suffice
✅ Good: Short prompt + screenshot/image, "fix padding" with visual, concise instructions, show what's wrong visually, use images for UI iteration
⚠️ Why: Visual aids are more efficient than text descriptions, shorter prompts preserve context, faster iteration, images are more accurate than descriptions, reduces ambiguity
🔧 Fix: Use images for UI issues, keep text prompts brief when visuals are available, include screenshots/clips for UI work, use images for design work

**Detect:** Long prompts for simple issues, text descriptions of visual problems, verbose explanations when image would suffice, no visual aids for UI work, trying to describe layout/design in words

---

### 9.3 Pattern Propagation (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** When discovering improvements, apply them across all similar projects.

❌ Bad: Fixing pattern in one project, leaving similar issues in other projects, inconsistent patterns across codebase, better patterns only applied to one project
✅ Good: When finding improvement, apply to all similar projects, maintain consistency across codebase, use scripts to find and update related codebases, update changelogs
⚠️ Why: Prevents pattern drift, reduces maintenance burden, ensures consistency, leverages improvements broadly, reduces context switching
🔧 Fix: When finding pattern improvement, search for similar projects/patterns, apply change consistently, use scripts to propagate changes, update changelogs

**Detect:** Pattern fixed in one place but not others, inconsistent implementations, improvements not propagated, manual updates needed everywhere, patterns only in one place

---

### 9.4 Multi-Agent Coordination Anti-Pattern (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Don't orchestrate multiple agents when a single pipeline suffices.

❌ Bad: Multiple agents for simple tasks, complex agent orchestration, agent coordination that adds latency without benefit
✅ Good: Single agent workflow, simple pipelines, avoid agent complexity, use multiple agents only when truly needed
⚠️ Why: Adds latency, complexity, difficult debugging, often unnecessary, wastes resources
🔧 Fix: Use single agent; only use multiple agents when truly needed; avoid unnecessary orchestration

**Detect:** Multiple agents for simple tasks, complex agent orchestration, agent coordination adding latency, unnecessary multi-agent patterns

---

### 9.5 Feedback Loop Integration (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Monitor rule effectiveness and update based on real-world patterns.

❌ Bad: Static rules never updated, ignoring common false positives, no rule effectiveness tracking, rules that don't improve
✅ Good: Track which rules catch most issues, refine based on patterns, monitor rule effectiveness, update rules based on feedback
⚠️ Why: Static rules become outdated, false positives waste time, no tracking means no improvement, ineffective rules persist
🔧 Fix: Monitor rule effectiveness; track which rules catch issues; refine based on patterns; update rules based on feedback

**Detect:** Static rules never updated, ignoring false positives, no rule effectiveness tracking, rules that don't improve, outdated rules

---

### 9.6 Cooperative Communication (Gricean Maxims) (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Agent↔user communication follows Grice's cooperative maxims. Quantity = what to include; Manner = how to order and word it.

| Maxim | Agent↔user communication | Already enforced by |
|---|---|---|
| Epistemic quality | Truthful, evidence-backed; no unsupported claims | §3.7–3.9, §4.1, Forbidden Phrases |
| Quantity | Match information units to task stage | §0.5, §3.5, §10.4 |
| Relation | Answer what was asked; stay on-scope | §7.3 → §9.7 |
| Manner | Clear, brief, orderly; lead with outcome | §0.1, §3.5 → §9.8 |

📍 See: `critical-rules-quick-reference.mdc` Cooperative Communication, `engineering-philosophy.mdc` §2.7

**Detect:** Unsupported claims in chat, essay answers to simple asks, off-topic narration, buried lede, generic "done" without evidence

---

### 9.7 Scope Relevance (Relation) (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Answer the user's actual request; do not expand scope silently in chat or code.

❌ Bad: Answering a different question; unrequested refactors or docs; silent scope creep; pursuing tangents without asking
✅ Good: Address the actual request; flag tangents as a brief note without acting; ask when ambiguous (§7.3)
⚠️ Why: Off-scope work wastes time, risks unwanted edits, buries the answer
🔧 Fix: Restate the ask if ambiguous; confine changes to scope; flag side issues, don't pursue unasked
📍 See: §7.3 Ambiguity Intolerance, §8.1 Pre-Execution Planning, `documentation-policy.mdc`, `taskplane-worker-cursor.mdc` File Scope

**Detect:** Unrequested refactors, answer to adjacent question, scope expansion without confirmation, unsolicited repo docs

---

### 9.8 Orderly Responses (Manner / Quantity) (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Agent↔user prose is clear, brief, and orderly; lead with the outcome. This governs chat and review text, not code clarity (§0.1 governs code).

❌ Bad: Burying result under preamble; wall-of-text; restating whole file/diff; generic "done" without paths or evidence
✅ Good: Outcome first; proportional depth (yes/no → short; audit → structured evidence); changed lines only in code citations
⚠️ Why: Readers need the result first; verbosity hides signal; under-answer hides verification status
🔧 Fix: Answer-first; 1–3 sentence summary of what changed and why; cite paths in backticks; state verification pending with commands attempted
📍 See: §3.5 Formatting Trap, §0.5 Chain-of-Thought Over-Use, `critical-rules-quick-reference.mdc` Output Format

**Detect:** Long lead-ins, full-file echoes, no clear takeaway, generic completion without paths/evidence, unstructured prose for structured data

