## Category 12: File and Directory Naming (Guidance)

**Scope:** Applies to source files, test files, and project-controlled artifacts (logs, exports, generated files in repo or tooling). Industry standard (Google, Maven, NASA): same principles for source and artifacts—lowercase, alphanumeric + hyphen/underscore, descriptive, version when relevant. **Guidance:** Prefer these rules; if project already has a convention, keep it; new projects follow below.

### 12.1 No Spaces in File or Directory Names (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Use underscores, hyphens, or language-appropriate case instead of spaces.

❌ Bad: `my project file.py`, `Reports/2024 Q1/`
✅ Good: `my_project_file.py`, `reports/2024-q1/` (or language convention)
⚠️ Why: Spaces break shell commands, scripts, URLs; require escaping or quoting
🔧 Fix: Replace spaces with underscores, hyphens, or camelCase/PascalCase per language
📍 See: Language-specific rules for source file naming

**Detect:** Spaces in file/dir names, names requiring quotes in commands

---

### 12.2 Safe Characters Only (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Restrict to letters (A–Z, a–z), digits (0–9), underscore, hyphen. Dot only for extensions or hidden files.

❌ Bad: `report!final$.txt`, `data#1.xlsx`
✅ Good: `report_final.txt`, `data-1.xlsx`
⚠️ Why: Special chars cause tool/script/URL issues across platforms
🔧 Fix: Use only [a-zA-Z0-9_.-]; avoid !$&*?#%

**Detect:** Special characters in file/dir names, punctuation other than . - _

---

### 12.3 Descriptively Concise (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Names clear and as short as reasonable; avoid cryptic or overly long.

❌ Bad: `x.py`, `the_file_that_contains_the_user_authentication_logic.java`
✅ Good: `auth_helper.py`, `UserAuthService.java`
⚠️ Why: Unclear names waste time; excessive length hurts typing and readability
🔧 Fix: Describe content/purpose in minimal words

**Detect:** Single-letter or cryptic names, names over ~40 chars without clear benefit

---

### 12.4 Case and Consistency (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Assume case sensitivity. Prefer lowercase unless language convention is PascalCase (e.g. Java/Swift source files). Use one convention per project.

❌ Bad: `Report.PY` and `report.py` in same project, mixing camelCase and snake_case for same file type
✅ Good: Lowercase for modules/dirs where language allows; match existing project convention
⚠️ Why: Case-insensitive filesystems cause collisions; inconsistency annoys tooling and peers
🔧 Fix: Prefer lowercase; follow existing project style; document convention

**Detect:** Mixed casing for same artifact type, inconsistent word separators in one project

---

### 12.5 Dates in Names (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Use YYYY-MM-DD or YYYYMMDD (with leading zeros) so lexicographic sort matches chronological order.

❌ Bad: `report_12_1_2024.txt`, `log-3-15-2024`
✅ Good: `report_2024-12-01.txt`, `log_20240315`
⚠️ Why: MM-DD-YYYY or DD-MM-YYYY sorts incorrectly
🔧 Fix: Year first, then month, then day; zero-pad month/day

**Detect:** Dates in file names not in ISO order, missing leading zeros

---

### 12.6 Version Suffixes (Guidance)

**Guidance:** Use zero-padded version numbers (e.g. v01, v02) so v10+ sorts correctly.

❌ Bad: `draft_v1`, `draft_v2`, `draft_v10` (sorts v1, v10, v2)
✅ Good: `draft_v01`, `draft_v02`, `draft_v10`
⚠️ Why: Lexicographic sort puts v10 before v2 without zero-padding
🔧 Fix: Zero-pad numeric suffixes (at least two digits if versions may reach 10+)

**Detect:** Version numbers in names without zero-padding, sort order broken at v10+

---

### 12.7 Productivity Pattern for Non-Source Assets (Guidance)

**Guidance:** For docs, exports, logs, or other non-source artifacts: optional three-part pattern **subject_date_code** (order flexible). Use **dashes** where spaces would go in subject; use **underscores** to separate the three parts. Code can be version (v01), initials, or draft/final.

❌ Bad: `New Hire Process 12-1-24 v1.docx` (spaces, ambiguous date)
✅ Good: `new-hire-process_20241201_V01.docx`, `20241201_report_DRAFT.pdf`
⚠️ Why: Sortable, script-friendly, consistent with industry (descriptive + date + identifier)
🔧 Fix: `subject-part-with-dashes_YYYYMMDD_CODE`; keep code segment distinct (e.g. caps for code)

**Detect:** Multi-word subjects with spaces, dates not YYYYMMDD, no separator between subject/date/code

---

## Summary: Critical Rules

These six patterns represent the most critical "making it work vs. making it right" violations:

1. **Ghost Layer Prevention** - No pass-through services
2. **Placeholder & Dead Code Ban** - No TODOs/FIXMEs in production
3. **Performance-First Collection Handling** - No I/O in loops
4. **Business Logic Location** - Keep domain pure
5. **Zero-Hallucination Policy** - Verify all APIs
6. **Hardcoded Secrets** - Use environment variables

**Quick Ref:** Arch: Ghost layers, fake abstractions, dead code, logic leakage, state confusion, god objects, file size limit, Strangler Fig | Perf: O(N²), unoptimized hot paths, performance blindness | Quality: Duplication, defensive comments, context blindness, over/under-engineering, formatting, magic values, warning dismissal | API: Hallucination, dependency issues, workaround-first | Security: Hardcoded secrets, missing validation, silent failures, resource leaks, error handling, global state | Testing: Mock mismatches, missing error paths, incomplete coverage, flaky tests | Context: Ignoring patterns, context window limitations, ambiguity intolerance, large context strategies, exhaustion patterns | Process: Pre-execution planning, AST-based detection | Agent: UI-first, verbose prompts, pattern propagation, multi-agent coordination, feedback loops, cooperative communication (9.6–9.8) | Modern LLM: Reasoning mode misuse, long context waste, multimodal misuse, structured output overuse, tool use anti-patterns, extended reasoning, large context misuse | Operations: Logging anti-patterns, metrics anti-patterns, error tracking, observability blindness | File naming: no spaces, safe chars, dates YYYY-MM-DD, consistency, productivity pattern (subject_date_code)

